AB  - Surgical education is focused on imparting the essential knowledge and skills required to diagnose the disease, decision-making regarding the need for surgery, performing the operative procedure, and providing perioperative care, including managing postoperative complications. However, the exponential growth of technology, the progressive decline in the doubling time of medical knowledge over the past three decades, and the need to train surgeons in multiple domains in addition to clinical and technical skills have posed new challenges in surgical education.[1] Disparities in the global economy, availability of skilled health-care workers, equipment, medical infrastructure, and access to technology have resulted in significant gaps in surgical education and care worldwide. Around 70% of the global population cannot access safe, timely surgical care, and an estimated 143 million essential operations are not performed yearly in low- and middle-income countries (LMICs).[2] To ensure standardization and quality assurance, advancing surgical education is required globally, as implementing standardized surgical education ensures that practitioners worldwide receive consistently high-quality training. This ensures that all communities have access to well-trained surgical professionals, reducing variations in surgical practices and enhancing patient safety. However, there are challenges in advancing surgical education worldwide, and surgeon leaders must focus on addressing them. HISTORY OF SURGICAL EDUCATION Understanding the evolution of surgical education is critical before looking ahead to the future. Early surgical training in the mid-16th century was based on the apprenticeship model that involved the surgical trainee observing the mentor without any structured training in a clinical environment for 5–7 years, followed by independent practice without any oversight.[3] Subsequently, William Halsted introduced the pyramidal model of surgical education.[3,4] In this model, 50% of the admitted residents have only a 1-year position. Of the remaining trainees who continue beyond 1 year, only 25% can become a house surgeon. The remaining trainees spend an indefinite period of observation and training with no guarantee of becoming staff surgeons. The pyramidal system produced excellent surgeons, and many of Halsted's trainees became chairs or professors of surgery in leading universities. However, the pyramidal model also depleted the trained surgeons' pool. The training in the pyramidal system is, to some extent, dependent on the relationship established between a dominant mentor and a docile trainee, which is not in accordance with scientific training principles. Hence, Edward Churchill introduced the "rectangular structure" model of surgical residency training.[3,4] As per the "rectangular structure" model, all the trainees who join the residency program would be trained for a fixed period, which is essential for surgical training. Subsequently, 50% of trainees who might choose to remain in the hospital or join as professors at other academic institutions will be retained. Surgical training in many countries is based on this model in which residents undergo training in core surgical principles for approximately 3 years, such as General Surgery in India, followed by another 3 years of specialized training in a particular field of surgery, such as urology or neurosurgery. The "rectangular structure" model precluded some of the limitations of the Halstedian pyramidal model. However, the time-based training model does not prepare surgeons for all the challenges in their careers. Hence, there was a gradual shift from time-based to competency-based surgical training. Competency-based training refers to an education model where trainees must demonstrate a required level of knowledge and skill (competency) on a task before advancing to the next task.[5] Competency-based training is not a novel concept, as it has been incorporated into the nonsurgical training of health-care workers since the 1970s. A limitation of the time-based model is that surgical trainees, in their initial part of residency, spend a considerable amount of time on clinical tasks that may be essential for patient care but do not directly align with the core surgical training. They achieve core competencies of surgical education only in the final years of training, which questions the need and efficacy of the early years of surgical training. In competency-based training, trainees must acquire critical skills relevant to a particular surgical specialty. Furthermore, the minimum expected level of performance at the various time points in their course is objectively graded. The available evidence suggests that competency-based training is more productive in imparting technical skills to surgical residents than conventional methods, which could potentially reduce the duration of surgical training.[6] The emergence of new technologies like laparoscopic and robotic surgery makes it imperative to train the next generation of surgeons in these novel techniques. Teaching surgical skills and procedures to trainees without harming patients has been challenging in the current era with the advent of minimally invasive surgery, which poses additional mechanical and visual limitations. Teaching surgical skills, especially minimally invasive surgery, to neophyte surgeons at the operating table on a live patient is no longer acceptable. However, a trainee learning surgical skills' visual and tactile components should work on tissue with the same appearance and handling qualities as living tissue. Proposed stepwise learning suggested for the surgeons before operating on patients includes initial training in box and virtual reality (VR) simulators followed by training in anesthetized live animals and soft embalmed human cadavers. However, the ideal surgical staircase to acquire skills may not be uniformly available. Hence, it is critical to advance surgical education globally to ensure standardization and quality assurance. HOW TO ADVANCE SURGICAL EDUCATION GLOBALLY? A standardized curriculum encompassing fundamental skills, specialized techniques, and the latest advancements in surgical practices should be promoted globally. The curriculum should include the basics of laparoscopic and robotic surgery, as a significant proportion of operative procedures would be performed by minimally invasive approaches. Furthermore, mandatory courses, including advanced cardiac life support, advanced trauma life support, and pediatric advanced life support, should be part of the curriculum. A standardized curriculum would ensure consistency and quality in training programs globally. Surgical challenges are often universal, and global collaboration facilitates the exchange of best practices, innovative techniques, and valuable experiences. Extensive data sharing during the COVID-19 pandemic is a prime example of international collaboration. Organizations such as "GlobalSurg" and "InciSioN" have played a critical role in initiating global collaboration in the surgical field.[7] Global collaboration enhances the collective knowledge of the surgical community and improves surgical care worldwide. Digital technologies and e-learning play a significant role in advancing surgical education, and the COVID-19 pandemic has accelerated their use. Digital platforms available for surgical training include web-based platforms, app-based platforms, and wearable technologies.[8] Internet-based platforms provide easy access to online resources such as surgical journals, e-books, operative videos, video lectures, and webinars. The virtual platform allows the trainees to repeatedly view operative videos and lectures to reinforce their understanding. Furthermore, these platforms can be regularly updated based on user feedback and emerging evidence. However, virtual platforms must be vetted by experts to ensure accuracy. This is especially important since trainees may use multiple videos of questionable quality available on various online platforms to update their operative skills. Smartphone-based applications are quite popular as most surgical trainees can access mobile phones with an internet connection. Applications like Touch Surgery offer over 100 surgical procedures from different subspecialties.[9] Each step of the operative procedure is depicted with interactive animations that permit trainees to understand surgical procedures better. It allows trainees to rehearse critical steps of the surgical procedure before entering the operating room. Wearable technology, such as Hololens from Microsoft and Oculus Quest from Meta, facilitates remote training of surgical residents by the mentor. These devices have a camera, microphone, and display screen. Mounting the device on the surgeon's head provides an immersive view of the operative field without interfering with the performance of the operative procedure. The "telestration" function allows the mentor to comment on images captured from the live streams and display them on the trainee's visual field, thereby facilitating telementoring.[10] Constant communication between the mentor and surgical trainee allows immediate feedback and guidance. Integrating artificial intelligence and deep learning into wearable technology can further enhance surgical education. To improve surgical education in LMICs, it is essential to have affordable and accessible digital technology. Most digital technology platforms require a good and stable internet connection, which may not be widely available in LMICs. Furthermore, the high cost of wearable technology may be prohibitive in many LMICs. Hence, second-generation VR platforms are focused on developing smartphone-compatible applications. Smartphones placed on Google Cardboard and other low-cost devices can replicate the features of more expensive VR headsets.[11] Incorporating artificial intelligence can help mimic the mentoring of trainees by expert surgeons. Digital technology can supplement conventional methods of supporting LMICs, such as expert surgeons from high-income countries visiting on a short-term basis to perform and teach surgeries. The aim is to build self-reliant surgical teaching programs capable of delivering quality surgical education in LMICs. Competency in technical skills alone is not sufficient to deliver modern, safe surgical practice. Nontechnical skills or soft skills, including interpersonal (communication, teamwork), cognitive (decision-making and situational awareness), and personal resource skills (coping with stress and fatigue), are essential for surgical training.[12] Royal College of Surgeons, Edinburgh, UK, played a key role in raising awareness and teaching nontechnical skills for surgeons worldwide. It is widely accepted that being a good surgeon is beyond just good operative skills; it is about being a good team player who listens and communicates well with patients and other health-care colleagues and encourages them to reach their full potential. Observing the evolution of surgical education and the shift toward competency-based models is fascinating. This approach acknowledges the multifaceted nature of surgical expertise and emphasizes technical skills, medical knowledge, and nontechnical skills like communication, teamwork, and professionalism. By moving away from the traditional "see one, do one, teach one" model, surgical education aims to produce well-rounded physician surgeons who are prepared to navigate the complexities of modern health care. Recognizing the challenges inherent in acquiring vast knowledge and skills within a limited training timeframe is crucial. Surgeon leaders are vital in driving this recognition and spearheading initiatives to adapt education and training. This might involve implementing ongoing self-reflection and feedback mechanisms, increasing specialized certification opportunities, and prioritizing development of nontechnical skills alongside technical proficiency. Furthermore, the transition toward a holistic review of trainee performance, focusing on core competencies within the broader health-care system, represents a significant paradigm shift. This approach ensures that trainees are competent in their technical abilities and emphasizes their ability to function effectively within interdisciplinary teams, communicate with patients and colleagues, and navigate ethical and systemic challenges. Overall, the future of surgical education appears to be moving toward a more comprehensive and adaptive model that addresses the diverse needs of trainees and the health-care system. By embracing this evolution and proactively addressing its challenges, surgical educators can better prepare the next generation of surgeon leaders for the complexities of modern health-care delivery.
