TY  - JOUR
TI  - Using EEG for Predicting User Preferences of Physical Compliance in Human-Robot Cooperation
PY  - 2018
PB  - Frontiers Media
SN  - 1662-5161
T2  - Frontiers in Human Neuroscience
DO  - 10.3389/conf.fnhum.2018.227.00116
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3389/conf.fnhum.2018.227.00116
DA  - 2018-01-01
AU  - Memar, Amir
AU  - Esfahani, Ehsan
LA  - en
KW  - Human–robot interaction
VL  - 12
AB  - Event Abstract Back to Event Using EEG for Predicting User Preferences of Physical Compliance in Human-Robot Cooperation Amir Memar1 and Ehsan T. Esfahani1* 1 University at Buffalo, Mechanical and Aerospace Engineering, United States Motivation and Objectives: Unlike traditional industrial robots which are designed to operate in an isolated fashion from human workers, co-bots (or collaborative robots) are intended to be used in direct physical interaction with human operators in a variety of applications such as effortless cooperative manipulation (co-manipulation), robot learning by demonstration and assistive robotics. In fact, the capability of physical interaction with a co-bot can improve the manipulation performance by integrating the repeatability and accuracy of the robot with the problem-solving skills of the human partner (Haddadin & Croft, 2016). While lots of progress has been made in terms of developing compliant controllers and motion planning strategies for a safe physical interaction, the ability of current co-bots to interact with humans in a truly intuitive way is still quite limited. The main challenge is to determine how to design interaction such that the robot can adapt to the user’s intention and enhances perceived comfort. Furthermore, individuals with different arm impedance characteristics require different compliance setup. Therefore, assessment techniques are necessary to understand the interaction effects on the user to improve the design accordingly. One approach for obtaining continuous objective measures about the user's cognitive state is the use of neuroergonomics methods to evaluate brain responses to physical interactions with co-bots with different controllers/planners. Methods: We have previously investigated the use of physiological monitoring such as eye tracking and electroencephalography (EEG) to assess operator performance in the interaction with remote robotic agents (Memar & Esfahani, 2018b). In this study, we extended our approach and focused on the use of EEG to assess human preferences of the robot compliance level in a physical interaction task. For this purpose, an experimental study has been carried out with an admittance-controlled robot arm which provides compliant interaction by mimicking the dynamics of a mass-spring-damper system (Hogan, 1985). This enabled the users to guide the robot end-effector in the Cartesian space based on adjustable dynamics between input forces and robot motions. 11 subjects (7 males and 4 females) were participated in the experiment and performed 4 different experimental scenarios consisted of two admittance-level (low- and high-damping) for two manipulation-task (gross and fine). In the gross manipulation, subjects were asked to guide the end-effector by turning around two virtual circles, as many as they can. In the fine manipulation, on the other hand, a precise star-tracking was performed with an emphasis on the number of errors (intersection with the boundaries of star shape). In fact, both fine and gross manipulations were considered in the experimental design to improve the generalizability of the EEG-based preference prediction across different tasks, contrary to our previous study which only considers fine manipulation (Memar & Esfahani, 2018a). Upon the ending of each experimental condition, subjects completed a NASA-TLX questionnaire for acquiring perceived difficulty. B-Alert X24 wireless EEG headset (from Advanced Brain Monitoring Inc.) was used to acquire EEG signals from 20 locations based on the 10/20 international EEG system. Signals were referenced to linked mastoids and a band-pass filtered in the range of 0.3 to 50 Hz. Independent component analysis was used for artifact removal using the implemented version of EEGLAB toolbox for MATLAB (Delorme & Makeig, 2004). The independent components predominantly driven by non-neural origins such as eye-blink artifacts and muscle activities were identified visually and cleaned from EEG data. Then, power spectral density and coherence measures were extracted for each 2-sec epoch data at theta, lower-alpha, higher-alpha, lower-beta, higher-beta and gamma bands for further analysis. The performance analysis and subjective assessments revealed that an appropriate virtual damping is task-specific. Statistical analysis based on a 2 by 2 [Manipulation-Type (gross and fine) × Virtual-Damping (low and high)] repeated measures analysis of variance (ANOVA) revealed significant interactions between Manipulation-Type and Virtual-Damping for both performance and subjective ratings of task difficulty. Results indicated that an intuitive interaction requires a lower damping when fast movements without certain accuracy (gross manipulation) are of interest. However, a higher damping improved the accuracy of performing the fine star-tracking task while increasing the virtual damping resulted in larger interaction forces (more physical effort). This indicates the importance of developing variable admittance controller that can understand the human intention of interaction and adjust the controller parameters to maximize human preference and comfort level. A Stepwise Multiple Linear Regression (SWMLR) method was utilized for dimensionality reduction and identifying the most correlated EEG measures of human preference in the physical interaction. SWMLR is a numerical approach that iteratively enters/removes predictors from the model based on the significant/insignificant main effects on the regression model. In this model, the EEG power spectral density and coherence were the predictor variables and the self-reported workload score obtained from NASA-TLX was the response variable. To obtain an overall workload score from the 6 dimensions of NASA-TLX, each dimension was weighted based on 15 paired comparisons over the dimensions (Hart & Staveland, 1988). For the SWMLR, Mahalanobis distance was used as the main criterion for entering or removing predictors with a p-value of 0.05 for entering and 0.1 for removing a predictor. Results: The SWMLR procedure led to a final set of 26 dominant EEG measure to predict the user’s preference of admittance level in the physical interaction. A leave-one-subject-out cross-validation approach was also used to evaluate the performance of the EEG-based regression model. Despite the existing differences between the actual self-reported scores and estimated one from EEG measure, the constructed regression model showed a reliable performance particularly in the discrimination between the preferred admittance (low-damping for gross and high-damping for fine manipulation) and the non-preferred conditions. Based on our results, we believed that objective assessment methods from neuroergonomics can improve our understanding of physical interaction with co-bots and also facilitate the design of adaptive controllers that can modulate their parameters based on human preferences. Although EEG signals are highly sensitive to the user's mental state and subjected to a low signal-to-noise ratio, valuable information can be obtained from EEG-based cognitive models for the assessment of human-robot interactions. Acknowledgements This material is based upon work supported by the National Science Foundation under Grant No.1502287. References Delorme, A., & Makeig, S. (2004). EEGLAB: an open source toolbox for analysis of single-trial EEG dynamics including independent component analysis. Journal of Neuroscience Methods, 134(1), 9–21. http://doi.org/10.1016/j.jneumeth.2003.10.009. Haddadin, S., & Croft, E. (2016). Physical Human–Robot Interaction. In Springer Handbook of Robotics (pp. 1835–1874). Springer International Publishing. http://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-319-32552-1_81. Hart, S. G., & Staveland, L. E. (1988). Development of NASA-TLX (Task Load Index): Results of Empirical and Theoretical Research (pp. 139–183). http://doi.org/10.1016/S0166-4115(08)62386-9. Hogan, N. (1985). Impedance Control: An Approach to Manipulation: Part II—Implementation. Journal of Dynamic Systems, Measurement, and Control, 107(1), 8. http://doi.org/10.1115/1.3140713. Memar, A. H., & Esfahani, E. T. (2018a). EEG Correlates of Motor Control Difficulty in Physical Human-Robot Interaction: A Frequency Domain Analysis. In 2018 IEEE Haptics Symposium (HAPTICS) (pp. 229–234). Memar, A. H., & Esfahani, E. T. (2018b). Physiological Measures for Human Performance Analysis in Human-Robot Teamwork: Case of Tele-Exploration. IEEE Access, 6, 3694–3705. http://doi.org/10.1109/ACCESS.2018.2790838. Keywords: EEG signal processing, human robot interaction, Admittance control, Brain computer interface (BCI), physical interaction Conference: 2nd International Neuroergonomics Conference, Philadelphia, PA, United States, 27 Jun - 29 Jun, 2018. Presentation Type: Oral Presentation Topic: Neuroergonomics Citation: Memar A and Esfahani ET (2019). Using EEG for Predicting User Preferences of Physical Compliance in Human-Robot Cooperation. Conference Abstract: 2nd International Neuroergonomics Conference. doi: 10.3389/conf.fnhum.2018.227.00116 Copyright: The abstracts in this collection have not been subject to any Frontiers peer review or checks, and are not endorsed by Frontiers. They are made available through the Frontiers publishing platform as a service to conference organizers and presenters. The copyright in the individual abstracts is owned by the author of each abstract or his/her employer unless otherwise stated. Each abstract, as well as the collection of abstracts, are published under a Creative Commons CC-BY 4.0 (attribution) licence (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/) and may thus be reproduced, translated, adapted and be the subject of derivative works provided the authors and Frontiers are attributed. For Frontiers’ terms and conditions please see https://www.frontiersin.org/legal/terms-and-conditions. Received: 11 Apr 2018; Published Online: 27 Sep 2019. * Correspondence: Dr. Ehsan T Esfahani, University at Buffalo, Mechanical and Aerospace Engineering, Buffalo, United States, ehsanesf@buffalo.edu Login Required This action requires you to be registered with Frontiers and logged in. To register or login click here. Abstract Info Abstract The Authors in Frontiers Amir Memar Ehsan T Esfahani Google Amir Memar Ehsan T Esfahani Google Scholar Amir Memar Ehsan T Esfahani PubMed Amir Memar Ehsan T Esfahani Related Article in Frontiers Google Scholar PubMed Abstract Close Back to top Javascript is disabled. Please enable Javascript in your browser settings in order to see all the content on this page.
